00:55:18.540 --> 00:55:20.180
And what's the time frame?

00:55:20.380 --> 00:55:23.300
So Nancy Grace Roman is really cool.

00:55:23.300 --> 00:55:30.740
It is also going to go out to L2 where JWST is sitting in part because it's an infrared telescope

00:55:30.740 --> 00:55:31.320
as well.

00:55:31.320 --> 00:55:32.900
It's focused in near infrared.

00:55:32.900 --> 00:55:33.880
So more similar.

00:55:33.880 --> 00:55:34.760
And the web one might get lonely.

00:55:34.760 --> 00:55:35.480
So it needs a friend.

00:55:35.480 --> 00:55:35.780
Yeah.

00:55:35.780 --> 00:55:36.160
Yeah.

00:55:36.160 --> 00:55:38.360
I mean, there are some other telescopes out there too.

00:55:38.360 --> 00:55:40.580
But yes, we need more friends.

00:55:40.580 --> 00:55:45.060
And so it is about, the mirror is about the same size as Hubble.

00:55:45.060 --> 00:55:48.400
But its optical prescription gives it a much wider field of view.

00:55:48.400 --> 00:55:50.300
So 100 times the field of view of Hubble.

00:55:50.300 --> 00:55:54.380
And it has way more detectors than pixels.

00:55:54.380 --> 00:55:55.880
About 300 megapixels.

00:55:55.880 --> 00:55:57.780
So there's 18 detectors.

00:55:57.780 --> 00:56:01.720
And every time we take a picture, all those detectors are going off.

00:56:01.720 --> 00:56:06.500
So there's also a lot more data volume coming down that we get to process.

00:56:06.500 --> 00:56:08.820
But a lot of cool things we can do.

00:56:08.820 --> 00:56:12.620
We can reach the level of the Hubble deep field very fast.

00:56:12.760 --> 00:56:17.580
We're going to cover about 50 times more space in the first five years of this mission

00:56:17.580 --> 00:56:19.480
than Hubble has in 30 years.

00:56:19.480 --> 00:56:23.980
So it's going to provide a lot of cool things for the community.

00:56:23.980 --> 00:56:26.040
It's also a survey telescope.

00:56:26.040 --> 00:56:31.960
So a lot of its time is dedicated to some surveys that want to be done to support the community.

00:56:31.960 --> 00:56:33.440
Looking for exoplanets.

00:56:33.440 --> 00:56:38.560
And they expect to find several thousand exoplanets during the first five years of the mission.

00:56:39.340 --> 00:56:44.020
Investigating dark energy and the expansion of the universe and the physics behind that.

00:56:44.020 --> 00:56:47.940
And so and other things that I'm sure astronomers will come up with.

00:56:47.940 --> 00:56:53.980
One of the cool things is that it will be launched to be compatible and collaborative with JWST.

00:56:53.980 --> 00:56:57.040
And LSST, one of the large ground-based missions.

00:56:57.040 --> 00:56:59.540
And Euclid, one of the European-based missions.

00:57:00.000 --> 00:57:04.920
So it's really cool to be in this era of astronomy where the missions can really be, you know,

00:57:04.920 --> 00:57:08.220
working together to make cool new discoveries and take data.

00:57:08.220 --> 00:57:08.860
That's fantastic.

00:57:08.860 --> 00:57:10.320
I haven't even thought of them working together.

